      "writtenOn": "2018-10-12T14:59:02Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, I think this is the one thing that got worse when switching to use context.  Especially in the case of Do(), where I would have rather used variadic arguments, but that would have required putting the step properties after the passed-in func, which would be really unreadable in the case of longer funcs:\n\nerr \u003d td.Do(ctx, func(ctx context.Context) error {\n   // Lots of lines here\n}, td.Infra(), td.Env(env), td.Name(...))\n\nWe do have a StepProperties struct which contains all of this information.  Maybe I can just change StartStep and Do to take a StepProperties instance and add builder funcs on to StepProperties. For example:\n\nerr \u003d td.Do(ctx, td.Props().Infra().Env(env).Name(\"named infra step with env\"), func(ctx context.Context) error {\n...\n\nI\u0027ll play with that idea a bit.",
      "parentUuid": "b677cf5e_f54c4616",
