        "id": 5205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-10-11T19:31:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\" I like that we propagate errors upward through steps in the same way that we propagate them in normal Go programs \"\n\nI agree, which is why I dislike defer td.FinishStep(ctx, \u0026err), or defer s.Done(\u0026err) as it was named in the last\niteration.\n\n\nI think FinishStep and Done are trying to do too much, both recording the sub-step we\u0027re at and also error reporting.\n\nThe code would be much simpler if recording steps was one process and returning errors just followed normal Go flow, i.e.:\n\nfunc someStep() error {\n  defer td.StartStep(\"Foo\").Done()\n\n  return nil\n}\n\nAnd count on calls to sklog.Errorf() to record errors.\n\nIf that\u0027s the way it worked then I\u0027d be fine with checking error responses from Do().",
      "parentUuid": "f3a9c4c6_4cbb58e4",
      "revId": "3400f4cb8ad9dbe096a38801c0068822646551e3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b9d924d4_6b064040",
        "filename": "go/task_driver/examples/basic/basic.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 154,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-10-11T19:42:43Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think turning a returned error into a failed step is central to making this work.  I don\u0027t believe that we we\u0027ll be able to correctly parse error logs and actually attribute the correct errors to the correct steps.  What if we return the error without logging anything?  If we follow our typical convention, we\u0027ll get a root-level failure with no information about which step actually failed.",
      "parentUuid": "fec5f0f8_0fc5389a",
      "revId": "3400f4cb8ad9dbe096a38801c0068822646551e3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1efb53ee_cd660484",
        "filename": "go/task_driver/examples/basic/basic.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 154,
      "author": {
        "id": 5205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-10-11T20:03:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\"I don\u0027t believe that we we\u0027ll be able to correctly parse error logs and actually attribute the correct errors to the correct steps.\"\n\nWriting to a stream such as stdout is an append, which is atomic, so order will be preserved.\n\n\"What if we return the error without logging anything?\"\n\nOn some level that\u0027s a bug in the recipe.\n\nBut let\u0027s back up, we want:\n 1. The ability to write regular Go code.\n 2. We want to know the step an error occurred at.\n 3. But we still want the ability for a step to respond or recover from an error and continue successfully.\n\nSimply returning an \u0027error\u0027 from every func covers 1 and 3, the only problem is 2, so why don\u0027t we\nemulate what we do in httputils with ReportError which handles both returning a \u0027safe\u0027 string to the user\nbut also logs the details contained in the \u0027error\u0027, i.e. add a \n\n  return td.Failed(ctx, err)\n\nOr we could count on the orderedness of the logs and failing to call sklog.Error* is considered\na bug that needs to be fixed.",
      "parentUuid": "b9d924d4_6b064040",
      "revId": "3400f4cb8ad9dbe096a38801c0068822646551e3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "97b8f3c6_034a712a",
        "filename": "go/task_driver/examples/basic/basic.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 154,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-10-12T12:14:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Another feature I was hoping to support was concurrency.  Or rather, I\u0027d like to write the framework in a way that doesn\u0027t restrict that feature.  If we might have multiple simultaneous steps, we can\u0027t do something like this:\n\nfunc someStep() error {\n    defer td.StartStep(\"Foo\").Done()\n\n    if err :\u003d doSomething(); err !\u003d nil {\n        td.FailCurrentStep(err)\n        return err\n    }\n    return nil\n}\n\nInstead, we need to pass the context around to ensure that the failure gets attributed to the right step.  I just wanted to be clear about why I didn\u0027t include any global current step and why I don\u0027t want to rely on log ordering.  So we have something like this:\n\nfunc someStep(ctx context.Context) error {\n    ctx \u003d td.StartStep(ctx)\n    defer td.EndStep(ctx)\n\n    if err :\u003d doSomething(ctx); err !\u003d nil {\n        td.FailStep(ctx, err)\n        return err\n    }\n    return nil\n}\n\nI think that\u0027s okay.  I\u0027m just afraid that people will forget to call FailStep, which is why I went to such lengths to pass the error pointer into the deferred EndStep.",
      "parentUuid": "1efb53ee_cd660484",
      "revId": "3400f4cb8ad9dbe096a38801c0068822646551e3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4cc483b7_ab57d6d9",
        "filename": "go/task_driver/examples/basic/basic.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 154,
      "author": {
        "id": 5205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-10-12T13:31:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027d forgotten about concurrency, but how are any logs besides Start/Stop/Fail going to be associated with a step? I.e. just calling sklog.Errorf() won\u0027t have enough info. Is there going to be a td.Infof(ctx,...) and td.Errorf(ctx,...)?\n\nIn reality we should probably be passing around an object\nthat supports some sort of Logging interface, and even better the std lib would support that, but it doesn\u0027t and that discussion is a mess: https://www.reddit.com/r/golang/comments/6bptkl/why_isnt_there_a_logger_interface_in_the_standard/",
      "parentUuid": "97b8f3c6_034a712a",
      "revId": "3400f4cb8ad9dbe096a38801c0068822646551e3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9e5c52bd_3a6ad8a7",
        "filename": "go/task_driver/examples/basic/basic.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 154,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-10-12T13:40:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, I hadn\u0027t worked that out yet.  My CL for cloud logging created its own logger for subprocess logs and step metadata and used labels to attach the step ID to every log entry.  A better solution is probably to add a LogContext to the sklog package which allows you to provide extra information, eg. labels, and then gets passed in to subsequent calls to sklog, eg.\n\npackage sklog\n\nfunc NewContext(ctx context.Context, labels map[string]string) context.Context {\n    ...\n}\n\nfunc InfoCtx(ctx context.Context, ...) {\n  getLogger(ctx).Info(...)\n}\n\n...\n\nfunc Info(...) {\n  defaultLogger.Info(...)\n}\n\n... or we make a giant sweeping change to always pass a context to sklog, or we add a logger type and use that instead of package-level Info() etc.",
      "parentUuid": "4cc483b7_ab57d6d9",
      "revId": "3400f4cb8ad9dbe096a38801c0068822646551e3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
